          "type": "thinking",
          "provider": "anthropic",
          "thinking": "The user wants to know if defining `extern` on `State` is sufficient for C ABI compatibility, or if nested structs like `Span` also need `extern`.",
          "finalTime": 1776863627342,
          "signature": "<redacted>",
          "startTime": 1776863626463
        },
        {
          "text": "Yes. `Span` must also be `extern` (which it already is).\n\nPer the [Zig language reference on `extern struct`](https://ziglang.org/documentation/master/#extern-struct): an `extern struct` guarantees C ABI layout — but that guarantee only applies to the struct itself. If a field's type is another struct, that inner struct must **independently** be declared `extern` to have a guaranteed C-compatible layout. A regular (non-extern) struct has implementation-defined field ordering and padding.\n\nYour code is correct: both `State` and `Span` are `extern`. The enums (`Diacritic`, `Tone`, `InputMode`) are already fine — they have explicit integer backing types (`u8`), which gives them a defined ABI size.",
          "type": "text",
          "finalTime": 1776863631870,
          "startTime": 1776863627342
        }
